ies, Nemerov reveals the surprising background of these bits of film and discovers unexpected connections between the war and Hollywood, from an obsession with aviation to Anne Frank's love of the movies. Beautifully written and illustrated, Wartime Kiss vividly evokes a world in which Margaret Bourke-White could follow a heroic assignment photographing a B-17 bombing mission over Tunis with a job in Hollywood documenting the filming of a war movie. Ultimately this is a book about history as a sensuous experience, a work as mysterious, indescribable, and affecting as a novel by W. G. Sebald.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aARTvAmericanvGeneral. 0aARTxHistoryvGeneral. 0aArt and history. 0aHISTORYvMilitaryvWorld War II. 0aHISTORYvModernx20th century. 0aHistoriography and photography. 0aPHOTOGRAPHYxHistory. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vMotion pictures and the war. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPhotography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMotion pictures and the war. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPhotography. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh  aAircraft.  aAlfred Eisenstaedt.  aAndrew Marvell.  aAnecdote.  aAnn Carter.  aAnne Frank.  aArchibald MacLeish.  aArsenic and Old Lace (play).  aBertolt Brecht.  aBoeing B-17 Flying Fortress.  aBomb bay.  aBomb.  aBosley Crowther.  aCary Grant.  aCombat Mission.  aCommand Decision (play).  aConfetti.  aConsolidated B-24 Liberator.  aDarryl F. Zanuck.  aDick Powell.  aDonna Reed.  aDown on His Luck.  aDr. Strangelove.  aEddie Muller.  aEloquence.  aEnola Gay.  aErskine Caldwell.  aFan magazine.  aFootage.  aG. (novel).  aGeoffrey de Havilland.  aGetty Images.  aGovernment Girl.  aGraflex.  aGregory Peck.  aHenry Fonda.  aHold Back the Dawn.  aHoward Hawks.  aHoward Hughes.  aI Wanted Wings.  aIn